{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9932,"record_hash":"sha256:d16c60b3af5589189e67c8e7122e4479d1ba02a0e8c422d9128fb3c9a9fe395f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:41:28.117Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n ### Resources, Tools, And Prompts\n \n [MCP server concepts](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/server-concepts)\n draws a useful line:\n@@\n \n That maps well to handoff:\n \n - `sessions` and `timeline` are context resources\n-- `related-detail` is a read tool\n+- `records` is a read tool\n - a future skill or prompt can teach the catch-up workflow\n \n The lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\n through one command that returns a wall of text.\n@@\n It should not copy these:\n \n - provider-native resume semantics for cross-provider handoff\n - automatic ingestion of all related transcript records\n - persistent generated summaries as the only source of truth\n+- one magic `handoff` command that hides the read path\n - cryptographic provenance or SLSA-style ceremony for v1\n \n+## Minimal Tool Draft\n+\n+The minimal agent-facing surface should be three read tools:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog sessions [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>] [--limit N]\n+but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--limit N]\n+but agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--limit N] [--cursor <cursor>]\n+```\n+\n+This is enough for an agent to:\n+\n+1. discover prior sessions\n+2. orient itself in the session and turn structure\n+3. read bounded transcript records only where needed\n+\n+There should not be a first-class `handoff` command. Handoff is the workflow the\n+agent performs with these tools.\n+\n+### `sessions`\n+\n+Purpose: answer \"what sessions should I inspect?\"\n+\n+Targeted form:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog sessions branch agentlog-turn-storage\n+```\n+\n+Untargeted form:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog sessions --limit 10\n+```\n+\n+The targeted form returns sessions related to a branch, review, or change. The\n+untargeted form returns recent project sessions. Both should return compact\n+orientation data.\n+\n+JSON should include:\n+\n+- requested target, if any\n+- `session_key`\n+- `updated_at`\n+- `turn_count`\n+- `record_count`\n+- `related_turn_keys`, only for targeted lookup\n+- source metadata: agents, providers, models, tool versions\n+- latest turn key and latest capture timestamp\n+\n+This command should not hydrate transcript records. It is an index card.\n+\n+### `timeline`\n+\n+Purpose: answer \"what happened across this session, and which turns look worth\n+reading?\"\n+\n+Example:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog timeline sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da --limit 20\n+```\n+\n+JSON should include one entry per capture turn:\n+\n+- `turn_key`\n+- `previous_turn_key`\n+- `capture_kind`\n+- `captured_at`\n+- `record_count`\n+- environment snapshot status\n+- observed branch/review/change target keys\n+- first and last record timestamps\n+- optional tiny previews of first and latest user text\n+\n+This command should not return full transcript records. It should stay cheap\n+enough that an agent can run it before deciding what to read.\n+\n+### `records`\n+\n+Purpose: answer \"show me the actual transcript records for this turn.\"\n+\n+Example:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog records sha256-9d942495afce65d863ef4d05e61ce2da \\\n+  --turn [REDACTED:entropy] \\\n+  --limit 200\n+```\n+\n+JSON should return:\n+\n+- `session_key`\n+- `turn_key`\n+- turn metadata\n+- ordered transcript records\n+- `next_cursor` when more records are available\n+\n+The command must be bounded by default. Backfilled turns can contain thousands\n+of records, so `records` should never accidentally dump a whole historical\n+session because one turn was large. If the agent needs more, it can follow the\n+cursor.\n+\n+### Optional Later Tool: `search`\n+\n+Search is useful, but not needed for the first handoff slice.\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog search <query> [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>]\n+```\n+\n+Add this only after the three read tools feel insufficient on real branches.\n+The first version can be plain full-text search over redacted transcript text\n+and turn metadata, returning session/turn hits that the agent can inspect with\n+`timeline` and `records`.\n+\n ## Challenge To The Initial Approach\n \n The core approach is right: let the next agent ask GitButler for relevant\n context. The parts I would push on:\n@@\n ## Agent-Facing Workflow\n \n A good first workflow is deliberately small:\n \n ```text\n but agentlog sessions branch <branch>\n but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--turns N]\n-but agentlog related-detail branch <branch> <session-key> [--context-before N] [--context-after N]\n+but agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--limit N]\n ```\n \n The exact names can change, but the shape matters:\n \n 1. discover related sessions for the current target\n 2. inspect a compact session/turn outline\n-3. hydrate only the windows that look useful\n+3. hydrate only the turns that look useful\n \n The user prompt can be simple:\n@@\n ## Non-Goals\n \n - no provider-native resume\n - no generated persistent handoff summary\n+- no magic `handoff` command for v1\n - no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n - no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n - no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n - no product-specific review browsing payloads\n \n ## Open Questions\n \n-- Should the CLI expose one ergonomic `handoff` command, or keep only generic\n-  primitives and let a skill orchestrate them?\n - Do we need a first-class \"session outline\" primitive in `but-agentlog`, or can\n   it be assembled cheaply from existing reads?\n - Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n@@\n ## Recommended First Implementation Slice\n \n-Do not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command yet.\n-\n-First add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform\n-handoff:\n+Do not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command.\n+\n+First add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform the\n+catch-up workflow:\n \n 1. enhance `agentlog sessions` so JSON includes session outline fields, not just\n    keys\n 2. add a bounded timeline command for one session\n-3. add a related-detail command that hydrates records around highlighted turns\n-4. write a small skill/workflow note that tells agents how to use those commands\n+3. add a bounded records command for one turn\n+4. write a small skill/workflow note that tells agents how to use those commands\n \n-That keeps the feature honest. If the workflow feels clumsy after using the\n-primitives on real branches, then add a convenience `handoff` command above\n-them.\n+That keeps the feature honest. If the workflow feels clumsy after using the\n+primitives on real branches, improve the primitives rather than hiding them\n+behind an opaque command.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:41:28.117Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}